Kombucha experiment meets Phyloseq

Experiment

For seven days, from July 27 to August 2, 2016, I drank 48 ounces per day of commercially-purchased kombucha. I tested my gut microbiome with a uBiome Explorer kit each day, as well as my mouth and skin microbiome at intervals during the experiment.

The results of each uBiome Explorer test are in the data directory in a series of JSON-formatted files.

rr ps.species <- phyloseq_from_JSON_at_rank(f,m,rank=)

Setting row names on a tibble is deprecated.

rr sample_data(ps)\(Date <- sapply(lapply(sample_data(ps)[['Date']], as.Date, origin = \1899-12-30\), # not sure why this origin gives correct answers as.character) sample_data(ps.species)\)Date <- sapply(lapply(sample_data(ps)[[Date]], as.Date, origin = 899-12-30), # not sure why this origin gives correct answers as.character) kombucha <- subset_samples(ps, Site == & Date > 016-07-26 & Date < 016-08-08) kombucha.species <- subset_samples(ps.species, Site == & Date > 016-07-26 & Date < 016-08-08)

The new object kombucha is a phyloseq object. Note that I created two versions, one that looked at the genus rank and the other at species. Both of them contain the same sample data, however:

To simplify later calculations and plotting, lets add another column (variable) Experiment that is set to either Kombucha on days I drank it, and None on days I didnt:

The data is still raw, containing the un-processed abundance data from the Illumina sequencer. Because there are differences in the way the DNA from the microbes are read in each sample (called reads), the total number of reads can vary significantly from sample to sample. For that reason, we generally dont compare the absolute abundances found in each sample; instead we calculate the percentages. To do that, we first must compute the normalized abundances:

rr kombucha.norm <- transform_sample_counts(kombucha, function(x) x / sum(x))

#transform_sample_counts(prune_taxa(taxa_sums(kombucha) > 10,kombucha), function(x){x / sum(x)}) kombucha.species.norm <- transform_sample_counts(prune_taxa(taxa_sums(kombucha.species) > 10,kombucha.species), function(x){x / sum(x)})

Species Level Analysis

uBiomes 16S technology only looks at the V4 subunit, with less than 300 reads in each direction. Thats plenty for most genus and above analysis, but it gets strained at the species level. Still, some of the species are visible, so lets look at the most common ones:

Note that because this is species level, this figure differs from genus one above because not every species within the genus is identifiable.
